03812nmm a2200601Ia 9780801474675DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20022002nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014746757 a10.7591/97808014746752doi  a(DE-B1597)534580  a(OCoLC)1163878552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a248.2/92211 aMoreira, Isabel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDreams, Visions, and Spiritual Authority in Merovingian Gaul /cIsabel Moreira. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn early medieval Europe, dreams and visions were believed to reveal divine information about Christian life and the hereafter. No consensus existed, however, as to whether all Christians, or only a spiritual elite, were entitled to have a relationship of this sort with the supernatural. Drawing on a rich variety of sources—histories, hagiographies, ascetic literature, and records of dreams at saints' shrines—Isabel Moreira provides insight into a society struggling to understand and negotiate its religious visions.Moreira analyzes changing attitudes toward dreams and visionary experiences beginning in late antiquity, when the church hierarchy considered lay dreamers a threat to its claims of spiritual authority. Moreira describes how, over the course of the Merovingian period, the clergy came to accept the visions of ordinary folk—peasants, women, and children—as authentic.Dream literature and accounts of visionary experiences infiltrated all aspects of medieval culture by the eighth century, and the dreams of ordinary Christians became central to the clergy's pastoral concerns. Written in clear and inviting prose, this book enables readers to understand how the clerics of Merovingian Gaul allowed a Christian culture of dreaming to develop and flourish without compromising the religious orthodoxy of the community or the primacy of their own authority.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian hagiographyxHistory. 0aChurch historyyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aDreamsxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aDreamsxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesyMiddles Ages, 600-1500. 0aMerovingiansxReligion. 0aVisionsxHistory. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147467540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801474675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801474675/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles